
It's a rarity among state school districts, and it was nice while it lasted: A fuel contract that locked Cobb County Schools into paying a mere $1.32 a gallon for diesel and $1.42 a gallon for unleaded expired Friday. With a new annual contract set to be awarded midmonth, school officials are bracing for the sticker shock that's already hit much of the nation. "Projections are that fuel will be at least a dollar more than what we're paying today," said Carroll Pitts, who oversees the district's transportation services &mdash; and that's if Cobb gets lucky. 

